Lokales Engagement as Countermeasure against Populism
PARIS – The parties that once dominated the western democracies have been profoundly shaken at their core.
Many – including in France, Italy, Greece, and the United Kingdom – have suffered crushing election defeats.
Others have changed so drastically that only the name remains.
The Republican Party of US President Donald Trump has little in common with that of former President Ronald Reagan.
These developments are similar everywhere in the West.
The leadership of the once dominant parties oscillate between denial and desperation, while populists are fishing for their traditional supporters.
Some refuse to acknowledge a legitimate reason for their defeat and dismiss their supporters as "pitiful" like Hillary Clinton did, just before she lost to Trump in 2016; others are too scared by the populist tide to launch a counterattack.
Neither denial nor self-satisfaction will resolve the entrenched political situation.
The Progressives must reorganize, and this starts with a diagnosis of the inadequacies of the traditional parties.
A part of the problem is that the traditional parties have not recognized the true themes of our time.
Still trapped on the old ideological battlegrounds, they dismissed the decreasing social mobility, the intensifying environmental crises, the increasing geographical inequality, the tensions regarding multiculturalism and other issues that are actually of concern to the voters.
They were the avant-garde decades ago.
Today they are alone in the woods and wondering where everyone has gone.
Social sciences could have an answer as to why the mainstream has strayed from the path.
The gulf between their objective analysis of reality and the policies of the governments has widened into a chasm.
In most Western countries, economists have long been aware of the growing disparity in income and other indicators between a few prosperous, globally benefiting cities and the rest of the country.
However, until French President Emmanuel Macron's government did it, no national head of government had implemented tax cuts based on residency.
As a result of this policy, 1% of French GDP is now primarily redistributed to the poorest parts of the country.
Traditional parties could also learn something by listening directly to voters instead of only through the filters of media and polling institutes.
In 2016, Macron's movement En Marche! started with the largest doorstep survey in French history.
What voters told the inquirers was then the basis of Macron's presidential election campaign.
For example, "La Grande Marche" had collected countless statements from women about harassment more than a year before the revelations about Harvey Weinstein's alleged sexual harassment of women, and Macron promised to address the problem in case of his election.
At the time, Macron's stance made him the target of his opponents' jokes; however, their laughter quickly faded with the rise of the #MeToo era.
However, a precise understanding of society alone is not enough.
The traditional parties are also suffering from poor organization.
They long believed that modern politics should be organized around elections, where activists distribute flyers at intervals and encourage candidates.
This was less cynicism than a symptom of an approach that views democracy as a marketplace consisting of state suppliers (the government) and consumers (citizens).
According to this view, the sole purpose of a party is to seize and maintain power.
It is no wonder that citizens and even party members feel ignored between elections.
Despite these weaknesses, established parties had a number of advantages that delayed their collapse.
In recent years, they had a technological advantage over less established opponents, and they were the only political actors with organized voter groups that could mobilize people to the polls, organize protests, and start petitions.
But this model no longer works.
Citizens refuse to be mere consumers of state policy today.
Along with a higher level of education came new demands for participation.
The voters want to be treated as political actors in their own right and not as pawns in the game of others.
Furthermore, governments are no longer the only providers of political measures.
This is one of the hard lessons we had to learn in the two years we worked alongside Macron in the Élysée Palace.
The most important political challenges today – climate change, religious extremism, digital upheavals, and gender equality – can no longer be solved by national governments alone.
These challenges demand profound cultural changes and, in most cases, measures at the sub- and supranational level.
And finally, technology has lowered the barrier to entry for political participation, so the traditional parties can no longer rely on the incumbent advantage and established support networks.
Anyone who can handle Google, Twitter, and Facebook well no longer needs a centuries-old party apparatus.
Political movements need to be reorganized accordingly.
The focus should be on concrete measures and not just on elections.
The formal administrative structure of a party should serve as an administrative „backoffice“; the frontend should be staffed by people on the ground.
Lokale Bürgerprojekte – which we call "local citizen projects" at La République En Marche! –
can range from literacy classes after school and integration programs for immigrants to cooperative vegetable gardens and digital training for seniors.
They're all about offering solutions tailored to local problems and thus strengthening community life.
We should now consider such projects as indispensable complements to state policy.
In the future, a party's ability to offer attractive ways for political and civic engagement will be crucial for its appeal.
And as they demonstrate their reform politics „live“ every day, the parties have already laid the ground for success on election day.
When voters refuse to listen to what's being said, the answer isn't to scream louder.
This is the hard lesson that traditional parties have learned.
Only those who demonstrate a commitment to improving people's lives, rather than simply winning elections, can win people over.
Restoring the connection to voters' concerns, therefore, goes hand in hand with adapting party organizations.
To offer a successful alternative to populism, we need progressive politics locally.
